# Implementation Plan: Nexus Kernel Orchestration Layer

This plan formally maps your deterministic `Kernel` abstraction out of `main.py` and into `nexus_kernel.py`, achieving full separation between system orchestration (`Kernel`), execution constraints (`Layer C`), state transitions (`FSM`), and entrypoint logic (`main`).

## Proposed Changes

### 1. Document System Contract
- **[NEW] `layer_d_kernel_prompt.md`**: Safely mapping your explicit Kernel Interface Spec systematically.

### 2. Implement the Orchestration System
- **[NEW] `nexus_kernel.py`**:
  - Implements the explicitly bounded `KernelResult` dataclass.
  - Generates the `Kernel` core orchestrator mapping strictly the 5 execution stages sequentially: *Ingestion -> Synthesis -> Policy (Layer C) -> Commit (FSM) -> Observation*.
  - Explicitly executes isolated logic against `mode="LIVE" | "REPLAY" | "SANDBOX"`. 

### 3. Migrate and Clean Entrypoint Logic
- **[MODIFY] `main.py`**:
  - Strip the `ExecutionEligibilityGate` loops and `replay_kernel.py` mapping routines completely out.
  - Implement a simple `Kernel` instantiation routing the mapped `IR_EventEnvelopes` seamlessly off exactly via `kernel.run(event_stream, mode="LIVE")`.
- **[DELETE/MODIFY] `replay_kernel.py`**:
  - Functionality merges or replaces cleanly into `nexus_kernel.py` reducing dependency chains completely securely.

## User Review Required
> [!WARNING]
> Because `main.py` presently drives numerous other legacy testing passes (like GraphBuilder Phase 1-3, DiffEngine Phase 4.5, ConflictDetector 6d), should I leave those pre-requisite graph construction loops inside `main.py` and ONLY wrap the final IR Event stream phase into `Kernel.run()`, or do you eventually plan to push ALL passes into the Kernel? 
> *(My plan currently leaves GraphBuilder passes in `main.py` and just wraps the final Layer-C event sequencing into the Kernel).*
